Which Startups are on the Rise?

Analysis of the Top 250 Startups

By Samiksha Boinpalli

1. Introduction:

The dataset used for this project was obtained from The Information, which is a website that publishes interesting news and articles related to the technology and business worlds. In 2024, the Information published data on 250 of the most promising startups; 50 from each year from 2020 to 2024. This dataset is called The Information 50 Database, and the companies within the dataset have been categorized into 8 different fields.

The reason that I chose this dataset is because of the growth in popularity and abundance of startups in recent years. I believe this trend reflects the increasing amount of competitiveness and innovation as more entrepreneurs seek to sell their products and ideas, which is truly exciting. Considering this, by analyzing this dataset, I hope to better understand and compare how industry sectors, time, and any other factors could play a role in a startups success.

What are startups or emerging companies and how do they work? (2025). Iberdrola. https://www.iberdrola.com

2. Data Preparation:

In order to obtain my data from the website, I had to manually scrape it, past it into a spreadsheet, and then download as a CSV. One challenge that I faced was that the notation valuations varied. The first steps I took to process and clean my data was taking several of the character variables that represented monetary values and converted them to numeric values, so that it would be easier to analyze these numbers. Then, I created two new variables of interest. One was the Net Money Raised, which was calculated by subtracting the money raised at publication variable from the current money raised variable. The other variable was The Valuation Growth Percentage, which was found by subtracting the valuation at publication variable from the current valuation variable, then dividing that value by the valuation at the time of publication variable, and finally multiplying that value by a 100. One challenge faced was that the data often had inconsistent notations. For instance, numbers in the millions were denoted as both M and millions. In addition, there was also values such as B, NA, Unknown, and more. To handle these inconsistencies, I used conditional or statement for different representations of millions, if statements to differentiate between millions and billions, and assigned NA to any values that were not numeric. In general, for any NA and unknown values, I converted them all to NA, so that they wouldnt disrupt any calculations with numeric values. Lastly, there was a total of 250 observations, representing 250 different startups; 50 from each year from 2020-2024.

3. Variable Descriptions:

Information about the Variables Used for Analysis.
Variable Name Type Description
name.of.company Categorical The name of the startup.
year.included Categorical The year that the startup was included on this list.
sector Categorical The industry sector that the startup belongs to.
revenue.at.time.of.publication Numeric The total revenue of the startup at time of publication
net.money.raised Numeric The total net change in the money raised by the startup from publication time to current time.
valuation_growth_percentage Numeric The percentage growth in the startup from the publication time to current time.

4. Univariate Analyses:

As evident, the distribution of startup sectors varies greatly, with Data & AI and Asia dominating the startup market with both sectors having counts of 38 startups in the top 250 startups. On the other hand, Devices & Robots is the least common sector in the Top 50 Startups with a minimum count of only 5 startups.

This histogram displays a right-skewed distribution of startup revenues at the time of publication, revealing that most of the startups revenues at the time of publication were less than 50,000 on the lower end with very few outliers reaching huge revenues. The mean revenue is 22 million, with a standard deviation of 36.84 million, proving that most revenues are concentrated on the lower end, however, there is still considerable variability in startup revenues during time of publication.

As shown above, the boxplot represents a right-skewed distribution of the Valuation Growth Percentage of startups. Additionally, the median of the Valuation Growth Percentage is 0 meaning that half of the startups saw negative growth and the other half saw positive growth. The mean valuation growth is 205.7 which is higher than the median, showing that a few startups with very high valuation growth are pulling the average upward and average valuation growth for startups is increasing/doubling.

This histogram displays a right-skewed distribution, of Net Money Raised by startups with a media net money raised of 0.3 million. The greatest amount of net money raised was 679 while the lowest was -90.76 million. As we see the median to be closer to the minimum net money raised, it can be concluded that while most companies experience modest growth in funding, only a few experience huge increases in funding.

6. Reproducibility

To ensure reproducibility of this project, I took several measures. First, I did not set the working directory and loaded all my packages in the top of my code. Additionally, I also avoided using any paths to my files when including the images within the report, so instead I directly put in the link address for the images. Lastly, I made sure to add in comments that explain my code as well as separate chunks of code to improve readability. By doing all these things, I made sure that my project was reproducible and understandable for others.

7. Choice Elements

The choice elements that I decided to use in this project are 5 or more in-line codes, creating two new variables of interest, formatting/parsing one string variable of interest, using a loop to process data, and lastly using an if statement to process data. First, I used in-line codes for all of my descriptive statistics when describing the graphs. Next, I created two new variables of interest when cleaning and processing my data and they are: net.money.raised and valuation_growth_percentage.Then, I used a loop to process the most recent valuation variable, converting different notations (M, B, million) into numeric values. I also implemented if statements within that loop to handle NA values and differentiate between millions and billions. Lastly, I formatted and parsed string variables of interest by combining similar sectors, such as Creator & Consumer with Consumer & Creator and AI Applications with Data & AI, and by extracting numeric values from monetary strings to create numeric variables for analysis. Except for in-line codes, all of the choice elements occured in the second chunk of code where I cleaned and processed the dataset.
